The most common bug to avoid in this task is an off-by-one error when indexing or comparing substrings of the input strings a and b. 

```python
def longest_common_substring_len(a, b):
    m = [[0] * (1 + len(b)) for i in range(1 + len(a))]
    longest, x_longest = 0, 0
    for x in range(1, 1 + len(a)):
        for y in range(1, 1 + len(b)):
            if a[x - 1] == b[y - 1]:
                m[x][y] = m[x - 1][y - 1] + 1
                if m[x][y] > longest:
                    longest = m[x][y]
                    x_longest = x
            else:
                m[x][y] = 0
    return longest
